<subSubSection id="1FD5651DFFD2FFC2F79CF6E76664EA4B" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="57703696FFD2FFC2F79CF6E76664EA4B" blockId="7.[2055,2644,2219,2640]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">
In his 1977 treatise, P. Hershkovitz regarded this species to be a subspecies of M. 
<taxonomicName id="90CF4D15FFD2FFC2F7F0F69067BDE9EE" box="[2148,2293,2411,2444]" class="Mammalia" family="Callitrichidae" genus="Callithrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="humeralifer">humeralifer</taxonomicName>
(then of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="90CF4D15FFD2FFC2F5B4F690671EE9D1" class="Mammalia" family="Callitrichidae" genus="Callithrix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Callithrix</taxonomicName>
. C. humeralifera). There is some slight regional variation in the intensity of the yellow on the tail and posterior part of the back. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FD5651DFFD2FFC2F793F5CC6805EAFD" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" type="multiple">
<caption id="03B0661EFFD2FFC2F793F5CC6805EAFD" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5730756" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5730756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5730756/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" targetBox="[1443,2022,2227,2634]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph id="57703696FFD2FFC2F793F5CC6805EAFD" blockId="7.[2055,2644,2219,2640]" lastBlockId="7.[1438,2646,2646,3466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="65BBEA84FFD2FFC2F793F5CC67FFEA32" box="[2055,2231,2615,2640]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">Distribution.</emphasis>
Brazilian Amazon, S of the Rio 
<collectingRegion id="950BF874FFD2FFC2FA4FF5AD6922EA15" box="[1499,1642,2646,2679]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
between the rios Madeira and lower Aripuana in the W and the Rio Canuma (= Cunuma) in the E.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FD5651DFFD2FFC2FA34F55E6896EB01" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" type="description">
<paragraph id="57703696FFD2FFC2FA34F55E6896EB01" blockId="7.[1438,2646,2646,3466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="65BBEA84FFD2FFC2FA34F55E69D3EAA4" box="[1440,1691,2725,2758]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 20-24 cm, tail 32-40 cm; weight ¢.280 g (males) and c.310 g (females). The Golden-white Tassel-ear Marmosetis yellowish-white, with pale golden or orange extremities and underparts. The tail is faintly banded with a darker shade of gold. The head is always white (without a crown patch), the face and ears are pink, and ear tufts are white and fan-like.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FD5651DFFD2FFC2FA34F49268F2EBE8" box="[1440,1978,2921,2954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="57703696FFD2FFC2FA34F49268F2EBE8" blockId="7.[1438,2646,2646,3466]" box="[1440,1978,2921,2954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="65BBEA84FFD2FFC2FA34F4926947EBE8" box="[1440,1551,2921,2954]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">Habitat.</emphasis>
Secondary lowland rainforest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FD5651DFFD2FFC2FA34F462687DEBB8" pageId="7" pageNumber="312" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="57703696FFD2FFC2FA34F462687DEBB8" blockId="7.[1438,2646,2646,3466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="65BBEA84FFD2FFC2FA34F46269E6EBD0" box="[1440,1710,2969,2994]" pageId="7" pageNumber="312">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Golden-white Tassel-ear Marmoset eats small fruits, nectar, gums, and small animal prey.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
